Inflation in Europe has eroded on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office in Luxembourg indicated.
The official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the key interest rate by saying that the decline in interest, with commodity price growth and the fall in unemployment, would lead to the generation of inflationary spirals.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "inflation must be deterred" in order to stop having to intervene on this subject at a later date.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent has been a record over the past 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area took off because of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market ratings increased by 88 per cent and soybean prices have also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 per cent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 per cent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the steering rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly in early December, so since 2002, it now has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Institute of Survey) has never previously seen such low socialist support, i.e. 13 percent.
For the faithful voters, the difference would represent, because of the greater determination of the opposition voters, more than two thirds (71 percent) support against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the survey, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is two percent in the entire population.
Of the faithful voters certain to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been so high, rising to 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population anticipates an increase and only one tenth predicts an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 per cent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, felt that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 percent trust the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that discontent with the Prime Minister can be addressed without change of government.
While after last October's riots, 35 per cent of the respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, this rate currently represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) felt that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question of the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents replied that they would certainly vote and the additional 20 per cent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 per cent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent would probably participate. According to the current intentions, the outcome of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 per cent of people would say no to registration fees in higher education, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees and 84 per cent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look at only the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees, respectively.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, unlike that this year the rate of VAT has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs trade triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, an increase of significantly higher value than a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "who had already flown" into major food stores last December, have no longer increased sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, the value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but the prices of turkey, walnut and poppy have risen sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to 139 forints only.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the bottle recorded including.
Only this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and the least expensive Cora.
According to our calculations, Cora has increased the price of his daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan have increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket and this year's cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent difference, while the difference between last year's cheapest and the most expensive one this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noted in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has perplexed trade, hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply on products as long as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forged.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was greater than 1 630 forints than last year and prices at the least increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some basic foods, the Institute of Statistics has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, of flour and egg.)
According to the daily basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in accepting the brutal increase in prices also by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at the prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long preserved food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important tails formed at the boxes of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is lower in the province, many multinationals complain to poll companies not even to reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago, MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma department at János Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person of a serious car accident left the hospital but shortly after he had to return there due to MRSA infection and since then the doctors have not been able to perform a major surgery because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Monitoring System nosocomiale, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsilitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a well resistant antibiotic bacteria that will rapidly proliferate under poor hospital conditions.
In the event of a temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicaemia, on elderly patients, of small weight or having a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the hospital's daily life.
Above all, we should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only it or we do not look for it, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SAs resist antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have appropriate antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, but the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and in homes for the elderly, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It is important to know that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases only occur if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the healing of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put gloves and protective masks. However, significant deficiencies are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemics, the patients should be removed from each other by at least 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the patients are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is less demonstrably or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSAs
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant spending on social security funds, which is why we fight this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has set up a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSAs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness
The official finding of the fatal accident caused by the 22nd arrondissement commissioner was drawn up.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd district, who has resigned from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led to drunkenness or dizziness, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding has been established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which has already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before taking the wheel.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the police station of the 22nd arrondissement crushed a 55-year-old man who stood in front of him when he shot, with his personal car, at Kossuth Lajos Street of the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian passage.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing does not constitute a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code a car that starts a turn must let the pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and requested his retirement because, according to the police, this accident has upset him a lot.
The investigation of this case is carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated with the investigating magistrates from the outset.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of EUR 400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund whose credit contract of EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also concerns budgetary financing for education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later as a result of the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of EUR 50 million for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the Metro Line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would reconsider the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of €8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans according to the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment commission.
Bulgaria, a paradise of the EU's real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market that is always the cheapest but that will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
At present, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses on the cheap seafront.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sunside", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly searching for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also increasing to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, business and office surfaces promise the highest amortization rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors already buy in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are looking at the same time to change their life, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. Along the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, said Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old delapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, the proximity of a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary residences (since last December Bulgaria has been mentioned among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving a medium or long-term surplus value.
The price of the capital's buildings continues to rise as demand increases.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices mainly exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six per cent Hungarian
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, professional meetings are ending on Tuesday, but on Wednesday, after the official opening, ministers' negotiations on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians coming from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the present time, there are strong discussions between developing and developed countries on this issue.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss accurate figures, but was prepared to sign an agreement on the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions from 25 to 40 per cent of 1990 levels up to 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit, without emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund set out in the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of directors consisting of probably 16 members within the framework of the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
Six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as an flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the 1990 level, regardless of the success of the signing of the "Post 2012 Agreement", and was prepared to reduce them to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and capacity.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signatories to the Kyoto Protocol had a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members of that time made a commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has undertaken to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system whose need was highlighted in the new IPCC report, the international scientific body, which obtained the Nobel Peace Prize of the United Nations to deal with climate change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the Earth's average temperature of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
The British Army units communicate on the video-sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with a view to becoming popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that was passionate about YouTube: special units in Afghanistan have been uploading video footage of Taliban operations since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken with miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London or the compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is essential
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 net sequences through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and broadcasts videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were posted on the net to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to publicize the actual objectives of the military presence abroad.
The propaganda published by this channel costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, communicated to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message because it justifies in a special form the validity of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is embarrassed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been posted on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, somewhat hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently packed up for the loading of these videos.
The Americans make the recruitment a little differently using the America's Army shooting game downloadable for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
