The forces of the mega strike gather
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will set up, on Friday, their strike commission, which will be responsible for coordinating the strike for an indefinite period of Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the Health Fund Act, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause important traffic caps as rail traffic will be stopped almost completely and employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1 p.m.
The League Unions will make known, Friday afternoon, the details of their strike on Monday, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The LIGA - MOSZ strike commission will also be formed, it will serve as coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and, starting on Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work for an indefinite period if they fail to reach agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in Parliament on the Health Fund Act, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Fund Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike commissions will meet and decide on further action.
According to the National Assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the Health Fund Act will take place only late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, important traffic closures are planned: railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of the public transport to Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are likely to be stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the road will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for strike, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report taking the strike for an indefinite period, while others reported a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Trade Union of Roads (VDSZSZ) failed to reach an agreement on minimum services, but, as Christmas holidays approached, more and more are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest's public transport will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., Budapest airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the League's Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Unions will strike for four hours, the Teachers Union and the Democratic Teachers Union have called for a strike for two hours and two hours to eight hours respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country alternately, the Health and Social Workers Union (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal on health reform and submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the pension to be implemented from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim seeks a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, that the functions that deserve to be passed on to the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Road Trade Union (VDSZSZ), attached to the League Trade Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has increased risk country
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital (Risk Analysis Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August, with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországert Mozart (Movement for a Better Hungary) increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning", the company notes that, in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur as a result of the worsening ethnic tension already existing between the Gypsy and non-gypsy population of Hungary".
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason for this.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma case to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Gypsies and Hungarians".
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, under the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular regarding the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following a greater publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and extreme right groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 giving themselves the name "national self-defence association".
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their adherents to defence missions (catastrophes, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, moreover, by referring to the incapacity of the police, the army, in other words the state," they added.
They pointed out that everything was going on according to the method which, based on the grudge of the political society and the parties, sought to disguise different political ambitions in a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civil character and association status is therefore only used to avoid the legal traps of registration of such associations in court, but it is also a political strategy.
The analysis points out that the Hungarian Guard's activity is a factor that also increases the risk from neighbourhood relations.
