A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in open access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were available for consultation only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an ex-victim or his successors.
The eleven States in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out "in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, had opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some of the victims of deportation.
The records of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been compiled after war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to prove their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual applications.
Yet, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the University Technische Berlin in 2006.
