What kind of insurance do I have?
Car insurance, which covers the driver in the face of possible accidents, involves a significant expenditure that will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, seniority of the driver's licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or use thereof, among others.
Having a car is the main thing.
And it's just that choosing the right car insurance is even harder than choosing the vehicle model.
And that's because choosing the right car insurance is even harder than choosing the vehicle model.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is realized by an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the premium granted and in return it becomes responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, seniority of the driving licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or use, among others.
Insurance companies set prices based on statistics, so that the higher the probability of an accident, the higher the rate to be paid.
It is for this reason that people over 25 and women must pay lower premiums, as statistics show that these people have a lower rate of claims than to their own prudence.
Similarly, using censuses, the companies concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will affect the frequency, and therefore the probability of an accident.
By increasing the frequency, probabilities increase.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
For this reason, the driver must study the situation in order to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
We will present here the most significant variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insurer, offers it a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 must face various disadvantages when making a contract with insurance at an affordable price, as can be the low experience in driving and driving licence seniority.
Although the ideal to be well insured is insurance at all risk, other more cost-effective options exist.
The most anticipated drivers can opt for risk insurance free of charge, so that they get insurance coverage at all risk but at a more affordable price.
This form of agreement implies that the client pays part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the amount of the claim that the customer pays will be determined according to the value of the premium, which will be higher the amount will be lower," says Luis Noguera, the head of Spain of First Europa, online insurance mediator.
Another option is extended third-party insurance, so that the customer provides protection to deal with damage caused to third parties, but for those caused on his own car.
In addition, it would be covered against theft, fire and vehicle loss.
A piece of advice.
If you are under 25 years of age, try to be careful and avoid accidents to the extent possible, as this will impact on the bonus, which can reduce the price of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction in the company's basic rate.
On the contrary, a penalty is an increase in the basic tariff.
"The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and its profit.
If the company has had a good year it will be able to afford to increase the bonuses, " explains Noguera.
Beyond the age of 25 it becomes easier for drivers to enter into a contract with insurance, since the rate of claims is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is preferable to choose any risk insurance with franchise.
"Normally young people cannot take advantage of the experience previously acquired after an accident", says the director of the European company in Spain and adds that the majority of accidents occur during the second year of driving, after passing the 'fear of the novice'.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children, it is best that he negotiates insurance at all risk, as long as his economic situation allows him.
Marriages with children are considered by insurers to be those with the lowest rate of claims, because the increases will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be insurance at all risk with deductible (may be 300 euros), or an extended third-party insurance from the third year of life of the vehicle when the insured has a high level of bonus.
"They have more casual driving and they have greater purchasing power to afford themselves the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchises," Judge Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, insurance at all risk with franchise is preferable (this is 150 euros), or extended third-party insurance when the insurer has a high level of bonus.
It must be said that motor insurance is something important, not only because it covers the driver in the face of possible accidents, but also because it represents a significant expense, that is why it is essential to study properly the insurance that suits us most according to our personal situation.
