Venus is the hellish twin of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere hostile to life, Venus looks more like Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightnings in the atmosphere and wind whirlwinds at poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightnings on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has now brought proof of this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the lightnings on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, reports Christopher Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprine theory, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, an angle stone of life.
This is not the case with Venus: "If there was a life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history," says Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington.
There should be few living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the hellish twin of the Earth, but she's still a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like the Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venetian research, as no more probes had been en route for exploration of this planet since the 1980s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles not only highlight the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first sight.
In addition to the wind whirlwinds already known at the North Pole, the researchers found a cloud whirlwind at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica italiana.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet described as an evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with a surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly recalls the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets have formed under similar conditions.
On both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes on Venus most of the atmosphere.
