They're not Warhols' boxes.
The one who connects the Swedish concepts and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's works list.
A large part of the eighty-ten Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago questioned the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of 1968 by Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now results in a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", whose former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum gave a gift in 1995 at the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which circulate on the international art market.
The ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatoric productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powder soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at Moderna Museet in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - presented hundreds of carton-made Brillo boxes: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather of their models, of exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time today speak of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered law into the history of art and auctions, as original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hutén Museum wrongly claimed later that about one hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have handed over to him.
Indeed, the 105 caisses of Hutén were produced in Malmö only in 1990 for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, of which two were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the painting was directly applied without a layer of background on laminated panels, using a roll of paint - moreover, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official Brillo-Boxes list," says Moderna Museet director Lars Nitttve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exposure material."
Already in July, the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the "thousand accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then there has been an inexorable silence.
